<TEXT>&#2;<DATELINE>2008</DATELINE><TITLE>Searching for the cause of Kawasaki disease â€” cytoplasmic inclusion bodies provide new insight</TITLE><BODY>Kawasaki disease (KD) has emerged as the most common cause of acquired heart disease in children in the developed world. The cause of KD remains unknown, although an as-yet unidentified infectious agent might be responsible. By determining the causative agent, we can improve diagnosis, therapy and prevention of KD. Recently, identification of an antigen-driven IgA response that was directed at cytoplasmic inclusion bodies in KD tissues has provided new insights that could unlock the mysteries of KD.&#3;</BODY></TEXT>